Security has been beefed up and roads closed around the Wanderers Cricket Stadium in Illovo, Johannesburg, where former US President Barack Obama will deliver the 16th Nelson Mandela Annual Lecture on Tuesday Mandela would have turned 100 years old on Wednesday. At least 15 000 people have been accredited to attend the annual lecture, including prominent leaders, presidents, heads of states and African royalty. Authorities have announced that CorletteDrive will be closed off between Ruud and Irene roads between 4am and 11pm, while only accredited vehicles and pedestrians will be allowed near the stadium. A contingent of Metro and South African Police Service officers has been deployed to ensure security. Obama, who made his first trip to Africa after his presidency, beginning in his native Kenya to launch his sister’s educational foundation, will speak about renewing Mandela’s legacy and promoting active citizenship in a changing world. READ MORE: Obama gathers 200 young African leaders for 5-day Joburg summit Key guests include former caretaker President Kgalema Motlanthe; former Italian Prime Minister Matteo Renzi; President of Cape Verde Jorge Carlos de Almeida Fonseca and his predecessor Pedro de Verona Rodrigues; President of Botswana Mokgweetsi Eric Keabetswe Masisi and his predecessor Ian Khama, and former President of Liberia Ellen Johnson Sirleaf. – African News Agency